<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="120f8986-d118-59ba-b221-72b691f04158" activityNameId="7e32a361-e0ee-4f18-a7b7-f0f931da4c76" parentActivityId="41fc050b-a9ae-5751-80b0-ba6b1ebc380b" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">potassium permanganate production, manganese dioxide oxidation</activityName>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Argucide</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Chameleon mineral</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Condy's crystals</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">Permanganate of potash</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">7722-64-7</synonym>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">This activity ends with the production of potassium permanganate. It consists of the manganese dioxide oxidation process, including materials, energy uses, infrastructure and emissions. The amount of hydrogen byproduct has been omitted from the dataset.</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">This dataset represents the oxidation of manganese dioxide, which delivers the co-products potassium permanganate (KMnO4) and, to a minor extent, potassium carbonate (K2CO3). Hydrogen, which is also a byproduct of this process, has been omitted from this dataset. </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">In the United States, potassium permanganate is primarily used for environmental applications, such as drinking water treatment (removal of tastes, odors, iron, and manganese, and control of trihalomethanes), wastewater treatment (destruction of hydrogen sulfide and other toxic and/or corrosive compounds, including phenols and plating wastes), and air purification (degradation of malodorous or toxic constituents in industrial off-gases). In other parts of the world (particularly Eastern Europe and India), the principal use of potassium permanganate is in chemical processing, especially the manufacture of synthetic organics. Numerous intermediates for pharmaceuticals and pesticides are made via permanganate oxidation, as are many fine organics, including flavoring. Significant amounts are also consumed for the oxidative destruction or precipitation of undesirable impurities, often ones that impart unwanted colors or odors. In recent years, KMnO4 has played a major role in the bleaching of indigo and other dyes for cotton twill fashion garments. Permanganate is also used for bleaching beeswax, natural sponges, jute fibers, and certain clays. Other important uses include surface treatment of carbon steels and stainless steels (descaling and desmutting, especially in wire manufacture), etching of rubber and plastics, and decontamination of nuclear reactors. Fish farmers utilize KMnO4 to prevent oxygen depletion and to control fish parasites.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Anhydrous potassium carbonate (K2CO3) is a white, hygroscopic, powdery material that deliquesces in moist air. The glass industry is the most important consumer of K2CO3. Large amounts are also required for potassium silicate manufacture. Potassium carbonate is additonally used for many organic syntheses, such as the production of potassium salts, and as a starting material for the production of drying, neutralization, and condensation agents. Potassium carbonate is used as a fertilizer for acidic soil. Other users are the electrical industry, the dye industry, the printing trade, the textile industry, the leather goods industry, and the ceramic industry. The food industry uses potassium carbonate as a leavening agent in baked goods, as a debitterizing agent for cocoa beans, and as an additive for drying raisins. Potash is also frequently used in the pharmaceutical industry as a raw material and auxiliary.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">This dataset is based on stoichiometric calculations as well as estimations based on data from a large chemical factory (Gendorf 2016).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Reidies, A. H. 2000. Manganese Compounds. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Sutter J. (2007) Life Cycle Inventories of Highly Pure Chemicals. Final report ecoinvent data v2.0, No. 19. Swiss Centre for Life Cycle Inventories, Dübendorf, CH.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Gendorf (2016) Umwelterklärung 2015, Werk Gendorf Industriepark, www.gendorf.de.</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled for Europe. Some values are based on data from a large chemical factory located in Germany. These are assumed to be valid for this geography.</text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The production of potassium permanganate consists of two steps: first a fusion process (either by the roasting process or the liquid-phase process), followed by the anodic oxidation of manganate(VI) to permanganate by electrolysis (Reidies 2000).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Reidies, A. H. 2000. Manganese Compounds. Ullmann's Encyclopedia of Industrial Chemistry.</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="1990-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Time of publications. Some values are based on data published by the Gendorf factory that were collected between 2011 and 2015. The time period has been adjusted accordingly. For more details, see the comments of the exchanges.</text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
    <flowData>
      <intermediateExchange id="e605c592-84b0-5858-be45-e5e3e53076a4" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" variableName="potassium_RP" casNumber="007722-64-7" amount="1.0" intermediateExchangeId="004f81b0-dd66-4146-a292-c2caa4353971" productionVolumeAmount="9917770.549" productionVolumeVariableName="RP_PV">
        <name xml:lang="en">potassium permanganate</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">In the United States, potassium permanganate is primarily used for environmental applications, such as drinking water treatment (removal of tastes, odors, iron, and manganese, and control of trihalomethanes), wastewater treatment (destruction of hydrogen sulfide and other toxic and/or corrosive compounds, including phenols and plating wastes), and air purification (degradation of malodorous or toxic constituents in industrial off-gases). In other parts of the world (particularly Eastern Europe and India), the principal use of potassium permanganate is in chemical processing, especially the manufacture of synthetic organics. Numerous intermediates for pharmaceuticals and pesticides are made via permanganate oxidation, as are many fine organics, including flavoring. Significant amounts are also consumed for the oxidative destruction or precipitation of undesirable impurities, often ones that impart unwanted colors or odors. In recent years, KMnO4 has played a major role in the bleaching of indigo and other dyes for cotton twill fashion garments. Permanganate is also used for bleaching beeswax, natural sponges, jute fibers, and certain clays. Other important uses include surface treatment of carbon steels and stainless steels (descaling and desmutting, especially in wire manufacture), etching of rubber and plastics, and decontamination of nuclear reactors. Fish farmers utilize KMnO4 to prevent oxygen depletion and to control fish parasites.</comment>
